properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for today. Lake effect snow is expected to affect the region today with local snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 cm expected by this evening. The higher snowfall amounts of 10 cm are expected over northern Wellington County, with lower amounts likely for areas further south including Kitchener - Waterloo and Guelph. Winds gusting up to 50 km/h will also lead to areas of blowing snow today. Travel in the area will be affected through late this afternoon. Note that there are snow squall warnings further west towards Lake Huron where higher snowfall amounts are expected. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Accumulating snowfall today. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm with possibility of up to 15 cm. Locations: southwestern Nova Scotia. Remarks: An intensifying low pressure system approaching from New England will move to lie near southwestern Nova Scotia today and will skirt the Atlantic Coast before heading away on Friday. Snowfall accumulations may reach as high as 15 cm over extreme southwestern Nova Scotia. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A multi-day episode of very cold wind chills continues. The coldest wind chill values will be between minus 45 and minus 50. Extreme cold conditions are expected to last through this week and even into Sunday for some regions. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds with higher than normal water levels. Maximum wind gusts: possibly exceeding 90 km/h. Storm surge: higher than normal water levels. Locations: the southeastern Gulf of St. Lawrence and Cape Breton Island. Time span: tonight into Friday. Remarks: An intensifying low pressure system approaching from New England will move to lie near southwestern Nova Scotia today and will track south of Nova Scotia on Friday. High waves and storm surge may affect the southern Gulf of St. Lawrence and Cape Breton Island tonight into Friday. This may cause some minor coastal flooding and overwash on north to northeast facing shorelines of the eastern mainland and Cape Breton during the high tides Thursday night and Friday. Wind warnings have been issued for eastern Nova Scotia. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls and local blowing snow today and tonight. Snow squalls are forecast to continue today due to cold northwesterly winds in the wake of a weak low pressure system. Local snowfall amounts of 5 to 10 cm are expected today, with an additional 5 to 10 cm possible tonight. Blowing snow will also accompany the snow squalls at times. The snow squalls are forecast to weaken by early Friday morning. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds with higher than normal water levels along the north coast. Locations: eastern Prince Edward Island. Maximum wind gusts: possibly reaching 90 km/h. Time span: tonight into Friday. Storm surge: higher than normal water levels along parts of the southern Gulf of St. Lawrence on Friday. Remarks: An intensifying low pressure system approaching from New England will move to lie near southwestern Nova Scotia today and will track south of Nova Scotia on Friday. High waves will break onto north facing shorelines, combined with higher than normal water levels for the southern Gulf of St. Lawrence tonight into Friday. This combined with a run of spring tides may cause some coastal flooding and overwash. The highest risk will be near the high tides tonight and Friday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High Storm Surge levels and large waves are expected to impact the coast. Locations: north facing shorelines from Notre Dame Bay to Ferryland. Maximum water levels: significantly exceeding high astronomical tide. Maximum wave heights: 8 to 11 metres, breaking upon approach to shore. Time span: midnight Friday night until Saturday afternoon. First high tide: after midnight Friday night. Second high tide: early Saturday afternoon. Remarks: Higher than normal water levels along the east and northeast coasts due to 60 to 80 cm of storm surge combined with 8 to 11 m waves are expected. Flooding and damage to coastal infrastructure are possible, especially in locations exposed to the north. Highest water levels are expected near high tide Friday night and early Saturday afternoon. ### High waves combined with the surge may cause damage along the coast. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Locations: Avalon Peninsula, Clarenville and vicinity, and Bonavista Peninsula. Total snowfall: generally 30 to 50 cm with 50 to 70 cm possible over parts of the northeastern Avalon Peninsula. Maximum wind gusts: northerly 100 to 120 km/h, with gusts to 140 km/h along exposed areas of the coast. Time span: early Friday morning until Saturday afternoon. Remarks: The combination of snow and strong winds will create widespread blizzard conditions with zero visibility in blowing snow. Heaviest snowfall will occur during the morning and afternoon on Friday when rates could exceed 5 cm per hour. Lesser rates will continue through Friday night. Winds will strengthen during the day on Friday, with the strongest gusts occurring Friday night.
